Author: blackjok3r#3181
Content:
First results back from new MoMoM test ... 
using freq=5 chain to migrate to freq=15 chains is producing results with 0 fails after 24H of sending 1 migrate TX every 120s.

Using 2 chains in their own cluster with freq=15 on both, transfering 1 TX each 120s there is also 0 failed migrate TXs. These chains are both sending back and fourth to each other 1 coin each 120s. 

I will leave this test running for a few more days, to make sure, but this seems to confirm @jl777c's theory that MoMoM issues are due to too fast notarisation frequecny. This has implications, but if this makes it work, we will next try a freq of 10, as this is the default for KMD chains. Also we need to try and see how many chains can be added to a cluster before the issue appears. My guess is that it probably wont, cause any issues adding more chains,as it seems to be an issue with the freq on the receiving chain only.

Author: Regnar#6164
Content: Question about scalability and block explorers. Are current block explorers set up to show scaling chains and their transactions along side one another?

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: would need an explorer for each chain

Author: Regnar#6164
Content: Thanks jl777. I'm not too familiar about how the explorers work exactly, but is it possible to design the block explorers to group blocks from multiple chains as a single "block" and just have field to indicate which chain the transaction happened on?

Author: Regnar#6164
Content: It seems like a custom solution imo

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: since the blocks are synchronized, it would be an arbitrary grouping

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: but anything is possible if you can make custom explorer

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: realistically aggregating all the chains into a single dataset would require incredible amounts of bandwidth

Author: Regnar#6164
Content: So in example, the explorers are synced, but as a regular user, could you not see your transaction information on an explorer itself?

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: you could look up your txid in the corresponding explorer, as normal

Author: Regnar#6164
Content: corresponding, as in N chain specific explorer?

Author: Regnar#6164
Content: or any old explorer.

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: as in you would know which specific chain the txid is for and you would use that chains explorer

Author: Regnar#6164
Content: I'm wondering if there's a way to aggregate the chains, even delayed or after blocks have been confirmed, in order to show results of total transactions among all chains for N block. Or if there is a way to make checking txid not reliant on knowing which chain/explorer to check. I could see that being a problem with 2 chains and even more so with 64 or more. What is our current method for providing proof of scaling capabilities?

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: they are independent blockchains

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: how would you prove that 64 blockchains exist and did the transactions they did?
